SON. 73

That time of year thou mayst in me behold

When yellow leaves, or none, or few, do hang Upon those boughs which shake against the cold, Bare ruin'd choirs, where late the sweet bird sang:

In me thou see'st the twilight of such day As after sunset fadeth in the west,

Which by and by black night doth take away, Death's second self, that seals up all in rest:

In me thou see'st the glowing of such fire

That on the ashes of his youth doth lie

As the death-bed whereon it must expire, Consumed with that which it was nourish'd by: --

This thou perceiv'st, which makes thy love more strong, To love that well which thou must leave ere long.
